727013f-c.title: Queens: Jamaica Avenue - 126th Street
727013f-c.text:
(1)
Jamaica Ave. (right foreground not shown), at the N.J.corner
of 126th Street, showing the former home of Capt. W.A. Lighthall.
This place was operated as a hotel by P. Opper in 1891. In 1922
it was known the Jamaica Saewgerbund Hotel operated by Mrs. Eaesebart.
It was demolished in March 1926.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
MAY BE REERODUCED.
(2)
The same, another angle.
April 1923.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
MAY BE REPRODUCED.
(3)
The same snowing another view of the same house.
1922.
Pugene L. Armbruster Collection.
MAY BE REPRODUUCD.

727014f-a.title: Queens: Jamaica Avenue - 126th Street
727014f-a.text:
Jamaica Ave., north side, between 126th and 127th Streets,
showing the Armbruster farmhouse, now gone, known as the Peter
Opper Roadhouse in 1891. See view west from 130th Street for more
data.
2994w
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.  '50N0
MAY BE REPRODUCED.

725841f-a.title: Queens: 126th Street - Jamaica Avenue
725841f-a.text:
126th Street, east side, between Jamaica Ave. (left) and
Eighty-ninth Ave. (right), showing partially in the background
the James H. Elmor house from 1870 to 1891. This information is
verified by T.F. Archer. However the 9ueens Atlas of 1891 shows
this property as that of James Elmilie.
April 1925.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
MAY BE REPRODUCED.
